\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Labor market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The labor market contains heterogeneous households (unconstrained and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hand-to-Mouth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 type of households age 15 to 100) and firms.
 Households choose the amount of working hours and their labor market participat
ion.
 Labor demand comes from firms posting their optimal amount of job vacancies,
 and a matching function brings vacancies and workers together.
 The model closes with bargaining between agents representing workers and
 firms, setting the market wage.
 The model aims to reproduce the level and behavior of Danish employment
 and wages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A difficulty when formulating the labor market is that there is heterogeneity
 on both the supply and demand side - a life cycle with workers of different
 ages and multiple sectors on the firm side.
 We therefore build the model so that the household side is age-specific
 and the firm side is sector-specific, but the two dimensions are never
 present simultaneously.
 In addition, there are two types of households, the constrained/impatient
 and the unconstrained/patient, and we solve the model so that both types
 have the same labor market decisions.
 The following are the key assumptions we make:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Firms cannot choose who they hire.
 Firms and workers meet randomly in the matching process, and once the meeting
 takes place, it is never optimal to send the worker away, irrespective
 of how old the worker might be.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optimal labor market participation and hours are age-specific but not sector
 specific.
 The worker cannot choose which sector she will be employed in and cannot
 voluntarily quit a job in one sector to join a different one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For computational reasons, we do not solve for the age distribution of workers
 inside each firm and instead impose that it is always the same for every
 firm.
 The data shows that the average age of workers is the same across firms
 of different sizes and for firms that are expanding or shrinking in terms
 of labor force size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, it is not the purpose of the model to unconditionally forecast
 long run trends in labor market participation or hours worked.
 Rather, these are exogenous inputs to the model's baseline based on detailed
 demographic projections including education, gender, and immigration status
 (Befolkningsregnskab).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Household problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is an exogenous number, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a,t}$
\end_inset

, of households of age 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 In this chapter, we interpret each household as containing a unit mass
 of agents who share the unemployment risk.
 We suppress the index within cohort heterogeneity, 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, as we let labor supply be identical for all households of a given age.
 Households aged 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 survive into the following age and period with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{a,t}$
\end_inset

.
 When a household dies its entire unit mass of members dies with it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $0<q_{a,t}^{e}<1$
\end_inset

 be the fraction of the household unit mass of workers employed in period
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 At the start of each period, agents in a household of age 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 can be in one of two labor market states: those who have kept their jobs
 from the previous period, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-\delta_{a,t}\right)q_{a-1,t-1}^{e}$
\end_inset

, and the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\left(1-\delta_{a-1,t-1}\right)q_{a-1,t-1}^{e}$
\end_inset

 that start the period without a job.
 The object 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{a,t}$
\end_inset

 is an exogenous age-specific job destruction rate.
 After decisions are taken in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and the market clears 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 are employed.
 From the household point of view employment evolves according to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{a,t}^{e}=\left(1-\delta_{a,t}\right)q_{a-1,t-1}^{e}+x_{t}q_{a,t}^{s}\label{eq:LOM_emp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is search effort and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the job finding probability.
 We now define a measure of labor force participation
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We calibrate this measure to be identical to the concept of the 
\emph on
gross labor force
\emph default
 (brutto-arbejdsstyrke) in aggregate, but not by age.,
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as the sum of the employed and the unsuccessful search effort:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{a,t}^{lf}\equiv q_{a,t}^{e}+(1-x_{t})q_{a,t}^{s}\label{eq:qlf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Total employment, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t}=n_{t}^{e}+n_{t}^{f}$
\end_inset

 , contains the employment of residents, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t}^{e}=\sum_{a}q_{a,t}^{e}N_{a,t}$
\end_inset

, plus a number of workers that are not residents, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t}^{f}$
\end_inset

 (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Non-resident"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Household problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We extend household utility to include disutility from hours worked, 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{a,t}^{e}$
\end_inset

, and from labor market participation, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{lf}$
\end_inset

.
 We have then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{a,t}(C_{a,t},D_{a,t})-\underbrace{Z_{a,t}^{h}}_{\text{Control}}\underbrace{\rho_{a,t}^{e}q_{a,t}^{e}}_{\text{Scaling}}\underbrace{\frac{\left(\lambda_{a,t}^{h}\right)^{\eta^{h}}}{1+\eta^{h}}\left(h_{a,t}^{e}\right)^{1+\eta^{h}}}_{\text{Hours}}+\underbrace{Z_{a,t}^{lf}}_{\text{Control}}\underbrace{\frac{\left(\lambda_{a,t}^{lf}\right)^{\eta^{lf}}}{1-\eta^{lf}}\left(1-q_{a,t}^{lf}\right)^{1-\eta^{lf}}}_{\text{Participation}}
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}$
\end_inset

 controls are exogenous to the household and used to control for stationarity,
 and, in line with Galí, Smets, and Wouters (2012), to eliminate the marginal
 utility of consumption from the first order conditions.
 This allows us to have the same search and hours decisions for HtM and
 unconstrained households, which greatly reduces model complexity.
 The objects 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{a,t}^{lf}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{a,t}^{h}$
\end_inset

 are calibration parameters.
 As hours vary by age in the data the disutility parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{a,t}^{h}$
\end_inset

 varies with age to match this pattern.
 Note that the CRRA disutility of labor market participation binds labor
 market participation 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{lf}$
\end_inset

 below one for all age groups; and as the probability of finding a job is
 also in the unit interval, so is employment 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{e}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Utility maximization is subject to the 
\emph on
budget constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Pi_{a,t} & =\underbrace{\left(1-\tau_{a,t}\right)w_{t}\rho_{a,t}^{e}h_{a,t}^{e}}_{\text{yearly wages after taxes}}\underbrace{q_{a,t}^{e}}_{\text{employment}}\label{B.C.}\\
 & +\left(1-\tau_{a,t}\right)b_{a,t}\underbrace{\left(q_{a,t}^{lf}-q_{a,t}^{e}\right)}_{\text{unemployment}}\\
 & +\left(1-\tau_{a,t}\right)b_{a,t}\underbrace{\left(1-q_{a,t}^{lf}\right)}_{\text{out of the labor force}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The household's after-tax wage depends on their effective tax rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{a,t}$
\end_inset

, the market wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}$
\end_inset

, age specific productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{a,t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 and finally the number of hours worked 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{a,t}^{e}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{a,t}$
\end_inset

 is the unemployment compensation received by those that are unemployed
 or out of the labor force, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{a,t}$
\end_inset

 summarizes all other budget constraint terms which do not appear in the
 problem at hand.
 As we do not make compensation contingent on search, the budget constraint
 simplifies to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{a,t}=b_{a,t}+\left[\left(1-\tau_{a,t}\right)w_{t}\rho_{a,t}^{e}h_{a,t}^{e}-b_{a,t}\right]q_{a,t}^{e}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which says that every household member earns 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{a,t}$
\end_inset

, and working members earn an additional wage premium 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-\tau_{a,t}\right)\left[w_{t}\rho_{a,t}^{e}h_{a,t}^{e}-b_{a,t}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 As the tax rate depends on the household's labor market participation and
 their number of hours worked, we write the wage premium more generally
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\Pi_{a,t}}{\partial q_{a,t}^{e}}$
\end_inset

.
 From this wage premium we define 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{a,t}^{b}$
\end_inset

 as the net benefit replacement rate of a household on the extensive margin
 of the labor market, i.e.
 the income after taxes and subsidies received by a household that is not
 employed, divided by the income received by that household if they found
 a job.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-r_{a,t}^{b}\equiv\frac{\partial\Pi_{a,t}/\partial q_{a,t}^{e}}{\left(1-\tau_{a,t}\right)w_{t}\rho_{a,t}^{e}h_{a,t}^{e}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This rate determines the incentive to search for a job and participate in
 the labor market.
 The net replacement rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{a,t}^{b}$
\end_inset

 is exogenous to the model and based on calculations from the Ministry of
 Finance's models of rules and administrative data (Lovmodeller).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effective tax rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{a,t}$
\end_inset

, is likewise a complicated function of income and deductions, but crucially
 depends on the number of hours worked by the household.
 Rather than specifying this function here, we define the marginal income
 tax rate directly as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\tau_{a,t}^{m}\equiv\frac{\partial\Pi_{a,t}/\partial h_{a,t}^{e}}{w_{t}\rho_{a,t}^{e}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The level of age specific marginal tax rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{a,t}^{m}$
\end_inset

 are also based on Ministry of Finance calculations, but move endogenously
 with shocks to tax rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now ready to maximize utility subject to the budget constraint and
 obtain the first-order conditions for participation and hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimal choice of hours
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first order condition for household 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{a,t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[1-\tau_{a,t}^{m}\right]U_{a,t}^{c}\frac{w_{t}\rho_{a,t}^{e}}{p_{t}^{c}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{a,t}^{c}\left[1-\tau_{a,t}^{m}\right]\frac{w_{t}}{p_{t}^{c}}=Z_{a,t}^{h}\left(\lambda_{a,t}^{h}h_{a,t}^{e}\right)^{\eta^{h}}\label{eq:hours_optimality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{h}=Z_{a,t}^{c}Z_{a,t}^{\tau}Z_{t}^{w}$
\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{t}^{w}$
\end_inset

 is used to control the impact of after-tax real wages.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{c}$
\end_inset

 is used to eliminate the wealth effect from this equation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The standard is to assume 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{c}$
\end_inset

 is a function of average marginal utility which in symmetric equilibrium
 equals the individual marginal utility.
 With the pooling assumptions within the unit mass of each household, and
 the assumption that all households are identical the average and the marginal
 are always identical but the symmetric equilibrium concept remains.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We let the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 terms be defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{t}^{w}=\frac{w_{t}}{p_{t}^{c}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c}
Z_{a,t}^{c}=U_{a,t}^{c}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

Eliminating the impact of real wages and marginal utility of consumption,
 the only remaining endogenous channel is from the marginal income tax rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{a,t}^{m}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h_{a,t}^{e}=\frac{1}{\lambda_{a,t}^{h}}\left[\frac{1-\tau_{a,t}^{m}}{Z_{a,t}^{\tau}}\right]^{\frac{1}{\eta^{h}}}\label{eq:hours_reduced}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By default, this effect is also eliminated by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{\tau}=\left[1-\tau_{a,t}^{m}\right]$
\end_inset

, however model users can enable endogenous effects of shocks to marginal
 taxes on hours worked by exogenizing 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{\tau}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We do not model the long run downward trend of the workweek.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{t}^{c}$
\end_inset

 rules out the income effect (higher consumption implying lower marginal
 utility) and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{\tau}$
\end_inset

 rules out the substitution effect of higher taxes (funding the expanding
 welfare state) in the baseline.
 An trend in preferences 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{a,t}^{h}$
\end_inset

 can be used to match an exogenously imposed trend in the baseline.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In that case, the elasticity of hours worked to the marginal tax rate is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\ln h_{a,t}^{e}}{\partial\tau_{a,t}}=-\frac{1}{\eta^{h}\left[1-\tau_{a,t}^{m}\right]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimal choice of labor market participation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inserting the household law of motion of employment, (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LOM_emp"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), in the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{lf}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:qlf"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we get an expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{lf}$
\end_inset

 (labor force participation) as a function of the household's choice of
 employment rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{a,t}^{lf}=\frac{q_{a,t}^{e}}{x_{t}}-\left(\frac{1-x_{t}}{x_{t}}\right)\left(1-\delta_{a,t}\right)q_{a-1,t-1}^{e}\label{eq:LOM_lf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this and the first order condition for the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 (employment) yields the optimality condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\underbrace{Z_{a,t}^{lf}\left(\frac{\lambda_{a,t}^{lf}}{1-q_{a,t}^{lf}}\right)^{\eta^{lf}}}_{\text{marginal disutility of search}}=\underbrace{x_{t}}_{\text{probability of finding a job}}\cdot\nonumber \\
\left\{ \underbrace{\frac{U_{a,t}^{c}}{p_{t}^{c}}\left(1-r_{a,t}^{b}\right)\left(1-\tau_{a,t}\right)w_{t}\rho_{a,t}^{e}h_{a,t}^{e}}_{\text{wage premium}}-\underbrace{Z_{a,t}^{h}\rho_{a,t}^{e}\frac{\left(\lambda_{a,t}^{h}\right)^{\eta^{h}}}{1+\eta^{h}}\left(h_{a,t}^{e}\right)^{1+\eta^{h}}}_{\text{disutility from hours worked}}\right.\nonumber \\
\left.+\underbrace{s_{a,t}\left(1-\delta_{a+1,t+1}\right)}_{\text{probability of surviving with a job}}\underbrace{\beta}_{\text{discount factor}}\underbrace{\left(\frac{1-x_{t+1}}{x_{t+1}}\right)Z_{a+1,t+1}^{lf}\left(\frac{\lambda_{a+1,t+1}^{lf}}{1-q_{a+1,t+1}^{lf}}\right)^{\eta^{lf}}}_{\text{saved disutility of search}}\right\} \label{eq:lf_FOC}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimality trades off current against future marginal utility, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the relevant utility discount factor and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{a,t}$
\end_inset

 is the survival rate.
 Extra engagement in the labor market today brings an immediate disutility
 of search, but with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 (the job finding rate) leads to additional employment.
 In case of finding a job we earn a wage premium 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-r_{a,t}^{b}\right)\left(...\right)$
\end_inset

, but get disutility from hours worked.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{a,t}\left(1-\delta_{a,t}\right)$
\end_inset

 we are alive and still have the job the following period and save the disutilit
y from having to search.
 Specifically, a retained job means we can lower 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a+1,t+1}^{lf}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1-x_{t+1}}{x_{t+1}}\right)$
\end_inset

 and still get the same level of employment, as shown by the law of motion
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{lf}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LOM_lf"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now define 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{lf}=\underbrace{Z_{a,t}^{c}Z_{a,t}^{\tau}Z_{t}^{w}}_{Z_{a,t}^{h}}Z_{a,t}^{\rho}Z_{a,t}^{r^{b}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{c}$
\end_inset

 eliminates the effect of the marginal utility of consumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{t}^{w}$
\end_inset

 eliminates the effect of real wages pr.
 productive hour, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{\tau}$
\end_inset

 eliminates the effect of marginal taxes.
 In addition, we define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z_{a,t}^{\rho}=\rho_{a,t}^{e}h_{a,t}^{e}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which eliminates the effect of age-specific productivity and hours worked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dividing through by 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{a,t}^{lf}$
\end_inset

, the participation condition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lf_FOC"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can be re-written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\underbrace{\left(\frac{\lambda_{a,t}^{lf}}{1-q_{a,t}^{lf}}\right)^{\eta^{lf}}}_{\text{marginal disutility of search}}=\underbrace{x_{t}}_{\text{probability of finding a job}}\cdot\\
\left\{ \underbrace{\frac{\left(1-\tau_{a,t}\right)}{Z_{a,t}^{r^{b}}Z_{a,t}^{\tau}}\left(1-r_{a,t}^{b}\right)}_{\text{wage premium}}-\underbrace{\frac{1}{Z_{a,t}^{r^{b}}}\frac{\left(\lambda_{a,t}^{h}h_{a,t}^{e}\right)^{\eta^{h}}}{1+\eta^{h}}}_{\text{disutility from hours worked}}\right.\\
\left.+\underbrace{s_{a,t}\left(1-\delta_{a+1,t+1}\right)}_{\text{probability of surviving with a job}}\underbrace{\beta\frac{Z_{a+1,t+1}^{lf}}{Z_{a,t}^{lf}}}_{\text{discount factor}}\underbrace{\left(\frac{1-x_{t+1}}{x_{t+1}}\right)\left(\frac{\lambda_{a+1,t+1}^{lf}}{1-q_{a+1,t+1}^{lf}}\right)^{\eta^{lf}}}_{\text{saved disutility of search}}\right\} 
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Branch lf_elasticity_derivation
