\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aggregating household employment with migration
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:labor_market_migration"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Population flows obey
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{a,t}=s_{a-1,t-1}N_{a-1,t-1}+I_{a,t}-E_{a,t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{a,t}$
\end_inset

 are immigrants and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{a,t}$
\end_inset

 are emigrants.
 Households making the choice described above are those surviving from the
 previous period.
 Those that survive from on period to another and stay in the country are
 denoted as; 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a-1,t-1}s_{a-1,t-1}-E_{a,t}$
\end_inset

.
 Emigrants 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{a,t}$
\end_inset

 are identical to other residents except that they leave the country.
 Employment for a household of age 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 evolves according to the accumulation-equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{a,t}^{e}=\left(1-\delta_{a,t}\right)q_{a-1,t-1}^{e}+x_{t}q_{a,t}^{s}
\]

\end_inset

Immigrants 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{a,t}$
\end_inset

 come into the country and we assume they obtain the same employment 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 as residents.
 We also assume that immigrants have the same search behavior as surviving
 households.
 However, they do not have an employment history in the country.
 This implies that some immigrants enter with jobs, so they do not have
 to search.
 This accounts for the employment quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{a,t}^{I}I_{a,t}$
\end_inset

.
 We have then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{a,t}^{e}=x_{t}q_{a,t}^{s}+q_{a,t}^{I}
\]

\end_inset

This sums to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\underbrace{N_{a,t}q_{a,t}^{e}}_{n_{a,t}^{e}} & =\left(1-\delta_{a,t}\right)\left(s_{a-1,t-1}-\frac{E_{a,t}}{N_{a-1,t-1}}\right)q_{a-1,t-1}^{e}N_{a-1,t-1}\\
 & +x_{t}\underbrace{q_{a,t}^{s}\left(s_{a-1,t-1}N_{a-1,t-1}+I_{a,t}-E_{a,t}\right)}_{n_{a,t}^{s}\equiv N_{a,t}q_{a,t}^{s}}+q_{a,t}^{I}I_{a,t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now assume that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{a,t}^{I}\equiv\left(1-\delta_{a,t}\right)q_{a-1,t-1}^{e}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
n_{a,t}^{e} & =\left(1-\delta_{a,t}\right)\left(s_{a-1,t-1}-\frac{E_{a,t}}{N_{a-1,t-1}}+\frac{I_{a,t}}{N_{a-1,t-1}}\right)n_{a-1,t-1}^{e}+x_{t}n_{a,t}^{s}\\
 & =\left(1-\delta_{a,t}\right)\frac{N_{a,t}}{N_{a-1,t-1}}n_{a-1,t-1}^{e}+x_{t}n_{a,t}^{s}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Given this construction, we do not have to know the number of immigrants
 and emigrants.
 All we need to know is the total population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Imposing the same age distribution on every firm
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ages_and_sectors"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result of the household's first order condition for participation/search
 is that employment will vary by age.
 However, we do not want to add the sectoral dimension to the disaggregated
 employment variable.
 In order to do this, when we solve the problem of the firm we do not solve
 endogenously for the age distribution of workers inside the different firms/sec
tors indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Instead we impose exogenously that this distribution is the same across
 all firms in the economy.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Different sectors will move differently over the cycle.
 And age specific population does not move evenly over time which implies
 neither will the labor force.
 All firms from all sectors hire the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

average job searcher
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from the currently available pool in the economy.
 As firms from different sectors hire different amounts over time the age
 composition of labor inside firms across sectors will differ, while it
 is the same in all firms within a sector.
 Keeping track of the age distribution within each firm/sector greatly increases
 the dimensionality of the model.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We also choose not to allow for differences in the job destruction rate
 across sectors arising from other factors.
 Evidence from administrative data on wage earners indicates that the average
 age of the labor force is independent of firm size and also uncorrelated
 with whether firms are reducing or expanding their employment.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Job Destruction and Job Finding Rates by Age in Danmark.
 Dream Working Paper, May 5, 2021.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We force the same distribution using the relationship
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{a,s,t}\equiv\frac{n_{s,t}}{n_{t}}n_{a,t}
\]

\end_inset

Given our assumptions, we never have to use the bigger object 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{a,s,t}$
\end_inset

, since on the production side the age distribution does not matter and
 so we only care about total employment inside the firm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Different average wages across sectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although in our model both labor supply and demand are anonymous, resulting
 in all firms hiring the same average worker looking for a job, and employing
 the same average employed worker in the economy, we observe in the data
 that average wages differ across sectors.
 It is possible that this reflects the heterogeneity of workers employed
 in different sectors, a feature which is ruled out in our model.
 In order to match the data on both employment and average wage acoss sectors
 we need a reduced form mechanism that will allow us to do so without breaking
 the two sided anonymity of the labor market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mechanism described here attaches different productivities to workers
 working in different sectors, while the workers themselves are identical
 wherever they happen to work.
 A three sector example helps illustrate it.
 We first impose the identifying constraint which attaches a relative sectoral
 productivity factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}^{i}$
\end_inset

 to sectoral employment, while keeping the total constant:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{1,t}^{w}n_{t}^{1}+\rho_{2,t}^{w}n_{t}^{2}+\rho_{3,t}^{w}n_{t}^{3}=\sum_{i}n_{t}^{i}=n_{t}
\]

\end_inset

Given this constraint, calculate the average wage per sector in the data
 and compute the ratios:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\rho_{1,t}^{w}}{\rho_{3,t}^{w}}=\frac{w_{t}^{1}}{w_{t}^{3}}=w_{t}^{13},\;\;\;\;\frac{\rho_{2,t}^{w}}{\rho_{3,t}^{w}}=\frac{w_{t}^{2}}{w_{t}^{3}}=w_{t}^{23}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note: the objects 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}^{ij}$
\end_inset

 are data for the period where data exists, and are forecasts for the subsequent
 periods.
 They are an exogenous input into the model.
 This allows for the endogenous calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{3,t}^{w}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{3,t}^{w}=\frac{n_{t}}{w_{t}^{13}n_{t}^{1}+w_{t}^{23}n_{t}^{2}+n_{t}^{3}}
\]

\end_inset

and of course of the other two as well.
 During data years we use observed average wages and employment, and in
 the forecasting years we use a forecast of relative average wages to calculate
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{j,t}^{w}$
\end_inset

.
 This mechanism preserves the search model.
 It is consistent with the randomness of matching.
 Which means the household problem is unaffected because of the initial
 identifying constraint.
 And it can be interpreted as a proxy for heterogeneity.
 
\end_layout

